<body class="ignore-math"><article class="exercise exercise-like"><article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(a)</span></h4>
<p>Suppose <span class="process-math">\(f^\prime(x)\neq{}f(x)\)</span> Show that if</p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation*}
\left(f\cdot g\right)^\prime(x) = f^\prime(x)\cdot g^\prime(x)
\end{equation*}
</div>
<p class="continuation">then<aside class="aside aside-like"><h5 class="heading"><span class="title">Advice and Encouragement.</span></h5>
<p>Don't let this formula frighten you. Recall that <span class="process-math">\(\exp(x)=e^x\text{.}\)</span></p></aside></p>
<div class="displaymath process-math" data-contains-math-knowls="">
\begin{equation}
g(x)=\exp\left({\int{\frac{1}{1-\frac{f(x)}{f^\prime(x)}}}\dx{x}{}}\right)\tag{1.4}
\end{equation}
</div></article><article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(b)</span></h4>
<p>Apply <a href="" class="xref" data-knowl="./knowl/eq-ProdDerivs.html" title="Equation 1.4">equation (1.4)</a> the function <span class="process-math">\(f(x)=x^n\)</span> and compare this to the results in Problem # 60 above.</p></article><article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(c)</span></h4>
<p>Suppose <span class="process-math">\(f(x)=e^x\text{.}\)</span> What would <span class="process-math">\(g(x) \)</span> be in this case?</p></article></article></body>
